I am a little lost here. Comments seem to differ.

@mtdowling I set the ``_raise_docstring_not_implemented`` method to be informative when developing or building subclasses on top of this base class. I could always set ``_docstring_writer`` to ``None`` and that will lead to a ``None`` object is not callable error. I just want the class to fail to generate documentation if the subclass does not specify a ``_docstring_writer`` to help with development and avoiding bugs as there are going to be a fair amount of Docstring class that will subclass from it in the future. What would you suggest?

@jamesls
It sounds like I am doing what you suggest. For example take the [ClientMethodDocstring](https://github.com/boto/botocore/pull/643/files#diff-5989425b25925188aeb4541546e0e61bR84) class. How does it differ from what you are suggesting?

Hi,

I am not that keen on this idea.

It would be easy to do something like:

    def LineModel(BaseModel):

        def estimate(self, data):

	    if data.shape[1] == 2:
		    self._model = LineModel2D
	    else:
		    self._model = LineModel3D
		
	    self._model.estimate(data)
	    self.params = self._model.params

However, I do not like the fact that LineModel2D has predict_x() and predict_y() functions, which LineModel3D has not. So combining them becomes awkward. Also, one model stores a line as (offset, theta) while the other stores (point, unit vector). So the unique LineModel should specify in its documentation that `params` do not have the same meaning in 2D and in 3D. Hence the rest of the code cannot be unaware of the fact it is written either for 2D or 3D.

While I agree in calling LineModel2D the current LineModel, I do not agree on making a single LineModel that would have different behaviours in 2D or 3D.

this can be simplified by giving classes `popover-regressions` and `popover-fixes` to the buttons, adding "Regressions" and "Fixes" to a `title` attribute, hen doing something like this:

```javascript
jQuery(function($) {
    $('.popover-regressions, .popover-fixes').popover({
            placement: 'right',
            trigger: 'hover',
            container: 'body',
            html: true,
            title: function() { return $(this).attr('title') },
            content: function() { return $(this).parent().find('.hidden').html() }
    })
})
```

